<font color="#FF0000">STUFF FOR COOK!</font><br>
<tt>Thu Sep 18  6:00:09 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Cook,<br><br>
If it ain't broke, don't try to fix it!<br><br>
Grief is normal, even if it is 30 years or so later. It is when those memories and automatic reactions go to work  underground in your head, and screw with your life to a point that you are suddenly in a crisis at the bottom of a deep, dark pit, when you have to worry. That's the way it was with me.<br><br>
I was so screwed up I thought I was normal. It took things almost blowing apart in my life to drive me to a shrink who took my head apart and said &quot;...and look at what we have here!&quot; to realize I was in serious trouble and needed professional help.<br><br>
I have been on that road now for over three years. Two years ago the 'Nam stuff really hit me hard between the eyes, and I bounced along the bottom again, real hard. I work with the professionals three to four times a month. My wife, my children, and some close, trusted friends see a real positive change. I still get &quot;...and that's why you behaved like that for the past 27 years!&quot; every so often, but it is in a positive and supportive sense. I have had to educate everyone close to me as I learned what was going on in my head to make it really work.<br><br>
Cook, I am now rediscovering what I had lost in 'Nam, like feeling happy and good about myself, experiencing joy and grief and sorrow, trusting, and all those things that make life the beautifull thing that it is, and was for me a long time ago, too. Do not think, however, this is a cure. There is none. I am only learning how to control it. Whenever I feel those old time automatic reactions start to rise up out of the Hell pit in my head, I now have the skills to recognize them and head them off at the pass, and respond in a way that won't be a thermonuclear reaction.  <br><br>
I have been told that I am one of the lucky ones who turned this stuff in my head into a successfull career. I guess they are right. After all these years, some of our brothers who are very severly affected and untreated are still sleeping under bridges, raiding garbage cans, bouncing from job to job, on drugs and alcohol, or in constant trouble with the law. PTSD can do that stuff to you, too.<br><br>
It is difficult for the uninformed to understand and appreciate that when you do the things you do, you are, at some subconscious level in you head, back in 'Nam getting even with Charlie or keeping a buddy alive.<br><br>
PTSD, the gift that keeps on giving! 
